1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:03,030
- I just finished reading
these 40 books about business,

2
00:00:03,030 --> 00:00:06,090
so I can cut out all the
fluff and save you time.

3
00:00:06,090 --> 00:00:08,700
You see, I've got an issue
with most business books.

4
00:00:08,700 --> 00:00:11,760
They have some great concepts
that anyone can learn from,

5
00:00:11,760 --> 00:00:14,070
but they're buried under
so much filler content

6
00:00:14,070 --> 00:00:16,380
that it takes ages to get to the gold.

7
00:00:16,380 --> 00:00:19,440
So as a millionaire
businessman myself, I wondered

8
00:00:19,440 --> 00:00:22,740
if I could use my knowledge
to cut through all the waffle.

9
00:00:22,740 --> 00:00:24,420
That's why over the last three months,

10
00:00:24,420 --> 00:00:27,390
I've made it my mission
to read all these books

11
00:00:27,390 --> 00:00:28,890
and note down the key points

12
00:00:28,890 --> 00:00:31,020
that will actually make you rich.

13
00:00:31,020 --> 00:00:33,840
So I've divided them into four categories.

14
00:00:33,840 --> 00:00:38,040
How to start with no money,
how to sell anything to anyone,

15
00:00:38,040 --> 00:00:39,840
how to market your business,

16
00:00:39,840 --> 00:00:42,450
and how to manage your money like the 1%.

17
00:00:42,450 --> 00:00:44,910
Now, you may think some of
these categories may not appeal

18
00:00:44,910 --> 00:00:47,370
to you, but trust me, put them together

19
00:00:47,370 --> 00:00:49,890
and they could make you a
force to be reckoned with

20
00:00:49,890 --> 00:00:51,360
in the business world.

21
00:00:51,360 --> 00:00:53,774
Let's get onto the first section.

22
00:00:53,774 --> 00:00:56,731
(energetic upbeat music)

23
00:00:56,731 --> 00:00:59,010
(paper rustling)

24
00:00:59,010 --> 00:01:00,540
So how to start with no money

25
00:01:00,540 --> 00:01:04,080
has got to be one of the
most Googled questions ever,

26
00:01:04,080 --> 00:01:05,400
so let's dive into it.

27
00:01:05,400 --> 00:01:07,860
Step one is to find your strengths.

28
00:01:07,860 --> 00:01:09,360
This seems pretty obvious,

29
00:01:09,360 --> 00:01:11,700
however, society has conditioned us

30
00:01:11,700 --> 00:01:14,700
to actually focus on
improving our weaknesses

31
00:01:14,700 --> 00:01:17,130
rather than doubling
down on our strengths.

32
00:01:17,130 --> 00:01:20,640
But the reality is, you can
be 10 times more successful

33
00:01:20,640 --> 00:01:23,760
as you focus on following
the path of least resistance.

34
00:01:23,760 --> 00:01:26,690
In other words, the stuff
you are already good at.

35
00:01:26,690 --> 00:01:30,000
"StrengthsFinder 2.0" says
your strengths come down

36
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:31,800
to a simple equation.

37
00:01:31,800 --> 00:01:35,070
Talent times investment equals strength.

38
00:01:35,070 --> 00:01:37,050
Let's use golf as an example.

39
00:01:37,050 --> 00:01:40,650
I enjoy playing at my local
club, although I'm not bad.

40
00:01:40,650 --> 00:01:42,210
I'm far from great.

41
00:01:42,210 --> 00:01:45,720
Suppose you took both Tiger
Woods and me at the age of 13

42
00:01:45,720 --> 00:01:48,750
and gave us the same amount
of coaching and practice.

43
00:01:48,750 --> 00:01:52,140
I'm willing to bet that every
hour he practiced would equate

44
00:01:52,140 --> 00:01:53,850
to about 10 of mine.

45
00:01:53,850 --> 00:01:55,620
This is because his inherent talent

46
00:01:55,620 --> 00:01:58,170
for the sport is significantly higher,

47
00:01:58,170 --> 00:02:00,450
given him a larger multiplier.

48
00:02:00,450 --> 00:02:02,430
That's why this book is so great

49
00:02:02,430 --> 00:02:05,370
as it helps you find your
most powerful multiplier

50
00:02:05,370 --> 00:02:07,680
so you can make more progress than others

51
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:09,270
in a shorter amount of time.

52
00:02:09,270 --> 00:02:11,160
Once you start thinking of weaknesses

53
00:02:11,160 --> 00:02:13,590
as an expense you need to minimize,

54
00:02:13,590 --> 00:02:16,200
your time will become
so much more effective.

55
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:18,030
You can always find people who can make up

56
00:02:18,030 --> 00:02:19,057
for your weaknesses.

57
00:02:19,057 --> 00:02:21,180
"How to win friends and influence people,"

58
00:02:21,180 --> 00:02:24,120
give some great networking
techniques you can try out.

59
00:02:24,120 --> 00:02:26,643
So before we move on, ask yourself this,

60
00:02:26,643 --> 00:02:29,010
have you been trying to become successful

61
00:02:29,010 --> 00:02:32,430
through fixing your weaknesses
or through developing

62
00:02:32,430 --> 00:02:34,710
and implying your innate strengths?

63
00:02:34,710 --> 00:02:37,140
Step two, come up with an idea.

64
00:02:37,140 --> 00:02:39,390
Now that you understand
the importance of playing

65
00:02:39,390 --> 00:02:42,030
to your strengths, it's
equally as important

66
00:02:42,030 --> 00:02:45,330
to choose a business idea
where you have an advantage.

67
00:02:45,330 --> 00:02:46,860
This is because every company

68
00:02:46,860 --> 00:02:49,710
that goes belly up has
one thing in common,

69
00:02:49,710 --> 00:02:51,487
they couldn't outrun the competition.

70
00:02:51,487 --> 00:02:54,480
"Zero to One" was written by Peter Thiel,

71
00:02:54,480 --> 00:02:57,416
the man who sold PayPal
to eBay for $1.5 billion.

72
00:02:57,416 --> 00:02:59,190
(cash register rings)

73
00:02:59,190 --> 00:03:02,280
What's even more impressive
is that his original team

74
00:03:02,280 --> 00:03:04,560
who received his personal mentorship,

75
00:03:04,560 --> 00:03:07,830
went on to establish companies
like YouTube and LinkedIn.

76
00:03:07,830 --> 00:03:10,740
Given the number of successful
businesses he's influenced,

77
00:03:10,740 --> 00:03:13,260
it's clear that he's mastered the secret

78
00:03:13,260 --> 00:03:14,904
of generating billion dollar ideas.

79
00:03:14,904 --> 00:03:15,780
(cash register rings)

80
00:03:15,780 --> 00:03:18,480
He says that billion
dollar business ideas come

81
00:03:18,480 --> 00:03:21,930
from betting on a contrarian truth.

82
00:03:21,930 --> 00:03:25,560
This is a real truth about how
people will act in the future

83
00:03:25,560 --> 00:03:28,710
that they aren't aware of
or don't want to admit.

84
00:03:28,710 --> 00:03:29,940
Steve Jobs believed

85
00:03:29,940 --> 00:03:32,370
that we didn't want a keypad on our phone.

86
00:03:32,370 --> 00:03:34,200
Very few people agree with him,

87
00:03:34,200 --> 00:03:36,870
especially as Blackberry
was the most popular phone

88
00:03:36,870 --> 00:03:37,703
at the time,

89
00:03:37,703 --> 00:03:40,530
and that thing was literally
riddled with buttons.

90
00:03:40,530 --> 00:03:42,870
I bet you guys don't even
remember Blackberrys,

91
00:03:42,870 --> 00:03:44,640
but he believed in his vision

92
00:03:44,640 --> 00:03:46,950
and was rewarded after
releasing the iPhone

93
00:03:46,950 --> 00:03:48,600
and changing the world forever.

94
00:03:48,600 --> 00:03:51,240
This isn't an isolated example.

95
00:03:51,240 --> 00:03:53,370
Uber believed that we
would feel comfortable

96
00:03:53,370 --> 00:03:55,260
getting into a stranger's car

97
00:03:55,260 --> 00:03:58,860
and Netflix believed we would
want to binge watch TV shows.

98
00:03:58,860 --> 00:04:01,350
If you are struggling to come
up with a contrarian truth,

99
00:04:01,350 --> 00:04:03,990
then give "Start with Why" a read

100
00:04:03,990 --> 00:04:07,050
as it will get you thinking
in the right kind of way.

101
00:04:07,050 --> 00:04:08,100
Perhaps you're not aiming

102
00:04:08,100 --> 00:04:10,290
to start a billion dollar business,

103
00:04:10,290 --> 00:04:13,260
but consider the things
you believe can be improved

104
00:04:13,260 --> 00:04:16,050
by adopting a slightly different approach.

105
00:04:16,050 --> 00:04:18,330
People will probably think
you're crazy at first,

106
00:04:18,330 --> 00:04:19,530
but that's okay.

107
00:04:19,530 --> 00:04:20,670
Going against the grain

108
00:04:20,670 --> 00:04:23,220
lets you carve out a massive advantage

109
00:04:23,220 --> 00:04:26,100
before anyone else even
notices what you're up to.

110
00:04:26,100 --> 00:04:29,010
This means you won't have
to worry about competition

111
00:04:29,010 --> 00:04:30,600
for a very long time.

112
00:04:30,600 --> 00:04:32,880
Step three is create a plan.

113
00:04:32,880 --> 00:04:35,730
Now you know what you're good
at and you've got your idea.

114
00:04:35,730 --> 00:04:36,930
You need to get very clear

115
00:04:36,930 --> 00:04:39,060
on how your business
is gonna be structured.

116
00:04:39,060 --> 00:04:40,980
Otherwise, you're just
gonna be running around

117
00:04:40,980 --> 00:04:42,030
like a headless chicken,

118
00:04:42,030 --> 00:04:44,107
not knowing where to focus your attention.

119
00:04:44,107 --> 00:04:47,160
"Business Model Generation"
is a collective effort

120
00:04:47,160 --> 00:04:50,760
from 470 entrepreneurs, professors,

121
00:04:50,760 --> 00:04:54,120
and CEOs across 45 different countries,

122
00:04:54,120 --> 00:04:56,700
they were able to break
down any business model

123
00:04:56,700 --> 00:04:58,890
into the essential nine building blocks

124
00:04:58,890 --> 00:05:00,570
that make up any business.

125
00:05:00,570 --> 00:05:03,540
They believe that many
business plans are overloaded

126
00:05:03,540 --> 00:05:07,710
with text and that using visuals
can be much more powerful.

127
00:05:07,710 --> 00:05:09,990
Let's do it together so
you can see how it's done.

128
00:05:09,990 --> 00:05:13,950
Rather than boring you with a
cliche lemonade stand example,

129
00:05:13,950 --> 00:05:17,790
which, let's be real, no
one's actually gonna do that.

130
00:05:17,790 --> 00:05:19,530
I'm going to outline a business

131
00:05:19,530 --> 00:05:22,500
that I reckon could be
a real winner right now.

132
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:25,470
Let's call it Timmy's Membership Builders.

133
00:05:25,470 --> 00:05:28,860
Firstly, Timmy loves watching
educational YouTubers,

134
00:05:28,860 --> 00:05:32,280
but gets frustrated because
lots of the advice is generic

135
00:05:32,280 --> 00:05:34,500
and doesn't really apply to him.

136
00:05:34,500 --> 00:05:37,350
So Timmy decides this is
what he wants to change.

137
00:05:37,350 --> 00:05:39,870
He wants to create a way
YouTubers can interact

138
00:05:39,870 --> 00:05:42,210
with viewers on a more personal level

139
00:05:42,210 --> 00:05:44,790
by building their membership platforms.

140
00:05:44,790 --> 00:05:47,250
This is Timmy's value proposition.

141
00:05:47,250 --> 00:05:50,250
Next, Timmy needs to
identify his customers,

142
00:05:50,250 --> 00:05:55,080
assuming that approximately
nought.1% of YouTube subscribers

143
00:05:55,080 --> 00:05:56,940
will want to join a membership,

144
00:05:56,940 --> 00:05:58,860
he should collaborate with YouTubers

145
00:05:58,860 --> 00:06:01,230
who have over 1 million subscribers.

146
00:06:01,230 --> 00:06:03,510
This strategy will generate enough value

147
00:06:03,510 --> 00:06:05,550
to justify his business venture.

148
00:06:05,550 --> 00:06:08,610
Now, Timmy needs to figure
out what channels he can use

149
00:06:08,610 --> 00:06:10,020
to reach his customers.

150
00:06:10,020 --> 00:06:14,220
He might choose email, DMs
or even physical letters.

151
00:06:14,220 --> 00:06:15,480
You are probably thinking

152
00:06:15,480 --> 00:06:18,180
if a YouTuber has over
a million subscribers,

153
00:06:18,180 --> 00:06:20,610
then they're gonna be
pretty hard to reach.

154
00:06:20,610 --> 00:06:22,500
But I can tell you from experience,

155
00:06:22,500 --> 00:06:24,840
if you have a good value proposition,

156
00:06:24,840 --> 00:06:27,480
then someone on their team
will see your message.

157
00:06:27,480 --> 00:06:29,550
We aren't as unreachable
as you might think.

158
00:06:29,550 --> 00:06:32,760
Building customer relationships
is the hardest part.

159
00:06:32,760 --> 00:06:35,760
That's why Timmy may have to
start off working for free

160
00:06:35,760 --> 00:06:37,830
to build up some case studies

161
00:06:37,830 --> 00:06:40,170
and then offer his first clients discounts

162
00:06:40,170 --> 00:06:41,910
for referring him to their friends.

163
00:06:41,910 --> 00:06:43,890
Focus less on what you can gain

164
00:06:43,890 --> 00:06:45,570
and more on what you can give

165
00:06:45,570 --> 00:06:48,000
as this form stronger relationships.

166
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,107
If you are struggling,
then you can always read,

167
00:06:50,107 --> 00:06:51,000
"Give and Take."

168
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:52,920
Now consider revenue streams.

169
00:06:52,920 --> 00:06:55,380
Timmy could choose to charge
a percentage of revenue

170
00:06:55,380 --> 00:06:58,380
for managing memberships,
freeing up the YouTuber

171
00:06:58,380 --> 00:07:00,450
to concentrate on producing videos.

172
00:07:00,450 --> 00:07:03,150
If Timmy took a 10% cut from a membership

173
00:07:03,150 --> 00:07:07,410
of 10,000 people each paying $5 a month,

174
00:07:07,410 --> 00:07:11,220
it would amount a $5,000
of monthly revenue.

175
00:07:11,220 --> 00:07:14,190
As the membership grows,
this figure will increase.

176
00:07:14,190 --> 00:07:16,290
Now Timmy needs to work out what he needs

177
00:07:16,290 --> 00:07:17,580
to make this all happen.

178
00:07:17,580 --> 00:07:20,910
These include his key
resources like a website,

179
00:07:20,910 --> 00:07:23,640
key activities such as advertising,

180
00:07:23,640 --> 00:07:25,290
and then key partnerships,

181
00:07:25,290 --> 00:07:27,840
which may include working
closely with a developer.

182
00:07:27,840 --> 00:07:30,660
Finally, Timmy needs
to calculate his costs.

183
00:07:30,660 --> 00:07:31,830
If he can do this business

184
00:07:31,830 --> 00:07:33,750
for less than what he expects to earn,

185
00:07:33,750 --> 00:07:35,250
then he is on the right track.

186
00:07:35,250 --> 00:07:37,890
If not, this evaluation will save him

187
00:07:37,890 --> 00:07:39,690
from disappointment in the future.

188
00:07:39,690 --> 00:07:41,640
That brings us to step four,

189
00:07:41,640 --> 00:07:43,950
building a minimum viable product.

190
00:07:43,950 --> 00:07:47,280
The harsh truth is many
entrepreneurs put their head down

191
00:07:47,280 --> 00:07:49,200
and work for months on a product,

192
00:07:49,200 --> 00:07:51,480
but don't realize that
they're building something

193
00:07:51,480 --> 00:07:53,467
that no one actually wants to buy.

194
00:07:53,467 --> 00:07:55,290
"The Lean Startup" suggests that

195
00:07:55,290 --> 00:07:56,850
instead of working super hard

196
00:07:56,850 --> 00:07:58,950
to create the most polished product,

197
00:07:58,950 --> 00:08:02,220
you should create something
called a minimum viable product

198
00:08:02,220 --> 00:08:03,930
or MVP.

199
00:08:03,930 --> 00:08:05,300
What's great about this is that

200
00:08:05,300 --> 00:08:07,950
it doesn't actually have
to cost you any money.

201
00:08:07,950 --> 00:08:10,560
The founder of Dropbox
made a short video showing

202
00:08:10,560 --> 00:08:12,900
how his file storage solution worked

203
00:08:12,900 --> 00:08:16,410
and managed to increase
his waiting list from 5,000

204
00:08:16,410 --> 00:08:20,760
to 75,000 people in the
space of a couple of days.

205
00:08:20,760 --> 00:08:22,590
The amazing thing about this story is

206
00:08:22,590 --> 00:08:24,390
that the video was fake.

207
00:08:24,390 --> 00:08:26,880
The product didn't even
actually exist yet,

208
00:08:26,880 --> 00:08:29,190
but he was then able
to use the waiting list

209
00:08:29,190 --> 00:08:32,220
to convince investors
that it was a good idea

210
00:08:32,220 --> 00:08:34,770
and then he was able to
make it into a reality.

211
00:08:34,770 --> 00:08:35,910
There are so many ways

212
00:08:35,910 --> 00:08:38,430
that you can make a free MVP nowadays,

213
00:08:38,430 --> 00:08:40,110
especially with the help of AI.

214
00:08:40,110 --> 00:08:41,250
If you want some inspiration

215
00:08:41,250 --> 00:08:44,760
then the "ChatGPT Millionaire"
is a great little read,

216
00:08:44,760 --> 00:08:47,640
you could use your MVP
to appeal to investors,

217
00:08:47,640 --> 00:08:51,240
launch a Kickstarter campaign,
find a business partner

218
00:08:51,240 --> 00:08:54,030
or bootstrap by reinvesting
the profits back

219
00:08:54,030 --> 00:08:55,680
into building your business.

220
00:08:55,680 --> 00:08:57,750
A crucial point to keep in mind is that

221
00:08:57,750 --> 00:08:59,490
if you are starting with no money

222
00:08:59,490 --> 00:09:01,710
and looking for any kind of funding,

223
00:09:01,710 --> 00:09:05,430
you must provide undeniable
proof of product demand.

224
00:09:05,430 --> 00:09:08,250
Step five, execute your vision.

225
00:09:08,250 --> 00:09:10,620
Now, having a plan, an idea,

226
00:09:10,620 --> 00:09:13,620
and an MVP isn't that precious.

227
00:09:13,620 --> 00:09:15,750
Lots of people make it to this stage,

228
00:09:15,750 --> 00:09:18,870
but what really matters is the execution.

229
00:09:18,870 --> 00:09:22,200
The crazy thing is most people
have the capacity to double

230
00:09:22,200 --> 00:09:24,930
or triple their income
by consistently applying

231
00:09:24,930 --> 00:09:26,430
what they already know.

232
00:09:26,430 --> 00:09:28,717
The issue is people don't put in the work.

233
00:09:28,717 --> 00:09:31,140
"The 12 Week Year" proposes a new way

234
00:09:31,140 --> 00:09:34,080
to get more done in 12
weeks than 12 months.

235
00:09:34,080 --> 00:09:36,930
It suggests that we should
break our year into four

236
00:09:36,930 --> 00:09:39,360
and think of those quarters as our year.

237
00:09:39,360 --> 00:09:42,480
This may sound silly as it's
still the same amount of time.

238
00:09:42,480 --> 00:09:44,760
However, this way of thinking forces you

239
00:09:44,760 --> 00:09:47,280
to confront your results
every three months.

240
00:09:47,280 --> 00:09:48,240
I don't know about you,

241
00:09:48,240 --> 00:09:50,430
but personally, when I've got a deadline,

242
00:09:50,430 --> 00:09:52,140
I work a lot harder.

243
00:09:52,140 --> 00:09:54,900
My businesses have a different
buzz around the office

244
00:09:54,900 --> 00:09:57,060
when we're nearing the end of the year.

245
00:09:57,060 --> 00:09:58,680
So by using this approach,

246
00:09:58,680 --> 00:10:01,740
instead of having that
buzz of motivation once,

247
00:10:01,740 --> 00:10:03,750
we can have it four times a year,

248
00:10:03,750 --> 00:10:06,510
as Parkinson law states, "Work expands

249
00:10:06,510 --> 00:10:08,850
to fit the amount of
time we allocate to it,"

250
00:10:08,850 --> 00:10:11,850
therefore, applying the
12 week year approach,

251
00:10:11,850 --> 00:10:13,620
we can actually achieve more

252
00:10:13,620 --> 00:10:15,390
and make significant progress

253
00:10:15,390 --> 00:10:17,430
towards building a business you want.

254
00:10:17,430 --> 00:10:19,830
However, this 12 week approach only works

255
00:10:19,830 --> 00:10:22,080
if you respect your deadlines.

256
00:10:22,080 --> 00:10:23,940
If you are the type of person who battles

257
00:10:23,940 --> 00:10:25,380
with procrastination,

258
00:10:25,380 --> 00:10:28,020
then "Extreme Ownership" is worth a read.

