305
00:12:13,320 --> 00:12:16,320
So how to sell anything to anyone.

306
00:12:16,320 --> 00:12:18,750
This section isn't just
important for business,

307
00:12:18,750 --> 00:12:20,910
but in all aspects of your life.

308
00:12:20,910 --> 00:12:23,370
Maybe you wanna persuade
your friend to help you,

309
00:12:23,370 --> 00:12:24,930
your boss to listen to you

310
00:12:24,930 --> 00:12:27,390
or even your parents to
give you more pocket money.

311
00:12:27,390 --> 00:12:30,810
The reality is we're
all selling in some way,

312
00:12:30,810 --> 00:12:33,330
although some of us are
much better skilled at it

313
00:12:33,330 --> 00:12:34,163
than others.

314
00:12:34,163 --> 00:12:35,850
Step one, set the frame.

315
00:12:35,850 --> 00:12:37,770
Believe it or not, most people fail

316
00:12:37,770 --> 00:12:39,930
before they even ask for what they want

317
00:12:39,930 --> 00:12:42,630
because they don't warm up
whoever they're talking to

318
00:12:42,630 --> 00:12:44,047
before trying to persuade them.

319
00:12:44,047 --> 00:12:47,190
"Pre-suasion" shares
techniques you can use

320
00:12:47,190 --> 00:12:50,340
to make people more receptive
towards your request

321
00:12:50,340 --> 00:12:51,570
before even asking.

322
00:12:51,570 --> 00:12:54,090
In this book, there's a
story about a consultant

323
00:12:54,090 --> 00:12:55,920
who was having a hard time

324
00:12:55,920 --> 00:12:59,460
because people kept asking
for discounts on his services,

325
00:12:59,460 --> 00:13:01,920
so he came up with a clever trick,

326
00:13:01,920 --> 00:13:03,510
before he tell them his price.

327
00:13:03,510 --> 00:13:05,970
He joked, "Well, as you can see,

328
00:13:05,970 --> 00:13:08,910
I can't exactly charge
you a million for this."

329
00:13:08,910 --> 00:13:11,850
After he started using
this joke, guess what?

330
00:13:11,850 --> 00:13:14,100
No one asked for a discount anymore

331
00:13:14,100 --> 00:13:16,237
and he could happily charge $75,000

332
00:13:16,237 --> 00:13:18,060
(cash register rings)
for his expertise.

333
00:13:18,060 --> 00:13:21,390
This sneaky little trick
is called price anchoring.

334
00:13:21,390 --> 00:13:24,120
It's all about that first
piece of information

335
00:13:24,120 --> 00:13:27,420
or that anchor that people latch onto.

336
00:13:27,420 --> 00:13:29,400
They then base their understanding

337
00:13:29,400 --> 00:13:31,290
of everything else around that,

338
00:13:31,290 --> 00:13:34,470
framing, however, extends
far beyond what we say.

339
00:13:34,470 --> 00:13:38,490
Non-verbal communication makes up 55%

340
00:13:38,490 --> 00:13:40,290
of all communication

341
00:13:40,290 --> 00:13:43,290
and much of that is
influenced by how we dress.

342
00:13:43,290 --> 00:13:45,030
That's why I recommend considering

343
00:13:45,030 --> 00:13:47,790
some of the advice in this
little book "Style & The Man,"

344
00:13:47,790 --> 00:13:49,500
remember, don't be in a hurry

345
00:13:49,500 --> 00:13:50,850
when it comes to setting the frame

346
00:13:50,850 --> 00:13:52,680
before asking for what you want.

347
00:13:52,680 --> 00:13:56,430
Trust me, using these strategies
can flip the whole scenario

348
00:13:56,430 --> 00:13:57,510
in your favor.

349
00:13:57,510 --> 00:13:59,527
Step two is build rapport.

350
00:13:59,527 --> 00:14:01,020
"The Art of the Deal" starts

351
00:14:01,020 --> 00:14:03,630
with Trump taking us
through a week in his life.

352
00:14:03,630 --> 00:14:06,180
The thing that struck out
to me was the sheer amount

353
00:14:06,180 --> 00:14:07,890
of calls he took per day.

354
00:14:07,890 --> 00:14:10,860
We are talking between 50 and 100 calls.

355
00:14:10,860 --> 00:14:14,490
This habit of regular check-ins
kept Trump at the forefront

356
00:14:14,490 --> 00:14:17,490
of people's minds, so when
a business deal came up

357
00:14:17,490 --> 00:14:19,200
that was advantageous for Trump

358
00:14:19,200 --> 00:14:22,320
or he had something to sell, it was easier

359
00:14:22,320 --> 00:14:25,517
to close the deal due to his
multiple nurtured connections.

360
00:14:25,517 --> 00:14:27,060
Today, we can achieve this

361
00:14:27,060 --> 00:14:29,820
by building a personal
brand on social media.

362
00:14:29,820 --> 00:14:33,270
Gary V emphasizes this in
his book, "Crushing It."

363
00:14:33,270 --> 00:14:36,000
Having a personal brand
increases our touch points

364
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:39,390
with people before we attempt
to sell anything to them.

365
00:14:39,390 --> 00:14:42,600
Therefore, increasing the
likelihood of future sales.

366
00:14:42,600 --> 00:14:45,630
Remember, people do business
with people they like.

367
00:14:45,630 --> 00:14:48,420
Step three, become more persuasive,

368
00:14:48,420 --> 00:14:51,090
so now you've set the frame
and built the rapport.

369
00:14:51,090 --> 00:14:52,890
You need to be able to persuade people

370
00:14:52,890 --> 00:14:54,547
to give you what you want.

371
00:14:54,547 --> 00:14:58,110
"To Sell Is Human" argues
that the most effective way

372
00:14:58,110 --> 00:15:01,620
to do this is to attune
with your prospect.

373
00:15:01,620 --> 00:15:03,870
I know that sounds a bit wishy-washy,

374
00:15:03,870 --> 00:15:05,970
but the experiment the book talks about

375
00:15:05,970 --> 00:15:08,160
makes this all start to come together.

376
00:15:08,160 --> 00:15:11,850
152 students were instructed
to negotiate the sale

377
00:15:11,850 --> 00:15:13,020
of a gas station.

378
00:15:13,020 --> 00:15:16,650
They were divided into two main
groups, buyers and sellers.

379
00:15:16,650 --> 00:15:20,280
The buyer group was further
split into three subgroups.

380
00:15:20,280 --> 00:15:21,960
The first subgroup was instructed

381
00:15:21,960 --> 00:15:24,630
to focus on being
empathetic to the sellers,

382
00:15:24,630 --> 00:15:26,940
the second on the seller's thoughts

383
00:15:26,940 --> 00:15:28,950
and the third on their own role.

384
00:15:28,950 --> 00:15:31,020
The highest number of
successful deals came

385
00:15:31,020 --> 00:15:32,460
from the subgroup that focus

386
00:15:32,460 --> 00:15:34,680
on understanding the seller's thoughts.

387
00:15:34,680 --> 00:15:36,420
Great deals always come when the buyers

388
00:15:36,420 --> 00:15:38,317
and sellers are in tune with each other.

389
00:15:38,317 --> 00:15:40,740
"Pitch Anything" makes a solid point,

390
00:15:40,740 --> 00:15:43,740
that when most people pitch,
they're too busy thinking about

391
00:15:43,740 --> 00:15:46,770
what they want and not what
their prospects are thinking.

392
00:15:46,770 --> 00:15:48,360
They assume that the audience care

393
00:15:48,360 --> 00:15:50,670
as much about their business as they do,

394
00:15:50,670 --> 00:15:53,040
but here's the harsh truth, they don't.

395
00:15:53,040 --> 00:15:55,650
Step four, collaborate effectively.

396
00:15:55,650 --> 00:15:57,480
Now that you are attuned to each other,

397
00:15:57,480 --> 00:16:00,540
what if you could transform
a sales negotiation

398
00:16:00,540 --> 00:16:04,350
into a collaboration, instead
of a one-sided process?

399
00:16:04,350 --> 00:16:07,200
Well, "Never Split the
Difference" suggests you can

400
00:16:07,200 --> 00:16:09,930
by asking something called
calibrated questions.

401
00:16:09,930 --> 00:16:12,480
Once you both feel like
you understand each other,

402
00:16:12,480 --> 00:16:14,640
you can then start using this technique

403
00:16:14,640 --> 00:16:16,710
as it directs the other person's attention

404
00:16:16,710 --> 00:16:18,060
towards your problems.

405
00:16:18,060 --> 00:16:21,390
These types of questions
normally start with what or how.

406
00:16:21,390 --> 00:16:23,340
With the ultimate question being,

407
00:16:23,340 --> 00:16:24,900
how am I supposed to do that?

408
00:16:24,900 --> 00:16:27,090
Let's say your landlord
was gonna put up your rent

409
00:16:27,090 --> 00:16:30,720
at $1,700 a month and you
didn't wanna pay that much.

410
00:16:30,720 --> 00:16:32,580
You could say, it seems like,

411
00:16:32,580 --> 00:16:34,350
you think your house is undervalued,

412
00:16:34,350 --> 00:16:37,320
but how am I supposed
to pay $1,700 a month

413
00:16:37,320 --> 00:16:41,040
when I only make enough money
to afford $1,500 a month?

414
00:16:41,040 --> 00:16:43,530
The key is to say it in a genuine way

415
00:16:43,530 --> 00:16:45,780
that doesn't seem confrontational.

416
00:16:45,780 --> 00:16:48,930
They should hear, "I
value your intelligence.

417
00:16:48,930 --> 00:16:51,150
Can you please help me solve my problem?"

418
00:16:51,150 --> 00:16:52,680
Asking this type of question

419
00:16:52,680 --> 00:16:54,990
will make the other
person think creatively

420
00:16:54,990 --> 00:16:57,120
or even lower their price.

421
00:16:57,120 --> 00:17:00,210
It's not a magic trick
and it won't always work,

422
00:17:00,210 --> 00:17:02,070
but it's definitely
worth giving it a shot,

423
00:17:02,070 --> 00:17:03,270
and here's a quick tip.

424
00:17:03,270 --> 00:17:05,580
If you are on the receiving
end of this tactic,

425
00:17:05,580 --> 00:17:09,120
never let another person's
problems become your problems.

426
00:17:09,120 --> 00:17:10,410
Understand them for sure,

427
00:17:10,410 --> 00:17:13,410
but remember, it's not
your job to solve them

428
00:17:13,410 --> 00:17:16,110
or you might just find
yourself caught in this trap.

429
00:17:16,110 --> 00:17:18,720
Good questions are really a superpower.

430
00:17:18,720 --> 00:17:21,780
That's why it's worth giving
"Better Small Talk" a read.

431
00:17:21,780 --> 00:17:24,060
Step five is closing the deal.

432
00:17:24,060 --> 00:17:26,490
You must never ever leave a conversation

433
00:17:26,490 --> 00:17:29,370
with a potential buyer
without a firm commitment.

434
00:17:29,370 --> 00:17:32,047
Otherwise, all the hard
work will be for nothing.

435
00:17:32,047 --> 00:17:34,530
"Objections: The Ultimate Guide

436
00:17:34,530 --> 00:17:37,770
for Mastering The Art and
Science of Getting Past No"

437
00:17:37,770 --> 00:17:40,770
recommends getting the
potential buyer to agree

438
00:17:40,770 --> 00:17:43,830
to a specific action on a fixed date.

439
00:17:43,830 --> 00:17:46,170
This is known as micro commitment.

440
00:17:46,170 --> 00:17:47,940
When trying to secure a commitment,

441
00:17:47,940 --> 00:17:50,310
be prepared for potential objections.

442
00:17:50,310 --> 00:17:53,100
For instance, if someone
says, "I'm quite busy,

443
00:17:53,100 --> 00:17:55,650
how about you call me next
week to arrange something?"

444
00:17:55,650 --> 00:17:57,667
A possible response could be,

445
00:17:57,667 --> 00:17:59,880
"My week is also looking pretty packed

446
00:17:59,880 --> 00:18:02,970
and I wanna make sure I can
dedicate the appropriate amount

447
00:18:02,970 --> 00:18:06,030
of time for our discussion
to ensure you don't miss out.

448
00:18:06,030 --> 00:18:08,370
Can we schedule our meeting right now?

449
00:18:08,370 --> 00:18:10,710
Would Friday at 03:30 work for you?"

450
00:18:10,710 --> 00:18:12,150
Obviously, you can adjust the time

451
00:18:12,150 --> 00:18:13,800
to whatever works for you,

452
00:18:13,800 --> 00:18:16,200
but see how that question
makes it much easier

453
00:18:16,200 --> 00:18:18,060
for the other person to say "Yes,"

454
00:18:18,060 --> 00:18:19,860
rather than objecting again.

455
00:18:19,860 --> 00:18:21,480
Of course, a bit of charisma

456
00:18:21,480 --> 00:18:23,640
can always help close a deal as well.

457
00:18:23,640 --> 00:18:25,500
Just think of the most popular closer

458
00:18:25,500 --> 00:18:28,680
on the TV show "Suits," Harvey Specter.

459
00:18:28,680 --> 00:18:31,320
Interestingly, the actor
is completely different

460
00:18:31,320 --> 00:18:32,790
from his role in the show,

461
00:18:32,790 --> 00:18:36,750
so this proves that charisma
can be faked to some degree.

462
00:18:36,750 --> 00:18:38,790
If you are interested in
learning more about this,

463
00:18:38,790 --> 00:18:41,321
consider reading "The Charisma Myth."

464
00:18:41,321 --> 00:18:43,966
(energetic upbeat music)

465
00:18:43,966 --> 00:18:46,650
(paper rustling)

466
00:18:46,650 --> 00:18:48,720
So how to market your business.

467
00:18:48,720 --> 00:18:51,240
Let's face it, you could
have the best product

468
00:18:51,240 --> 00:18:53,040
or service in the world,

469
00:18:53,040 --> 00:18:55,860
but what's the use if
nobody knows about it?

470
00:18:55,860 --> 00:18:59,280
Step one is developing your
unique selling proposition.

471
00:18:59,280 --> 00:19:02,640
Ever found yourself wondering
why some businesses explode

472
00:19:02,640 --> 00:19:04,620
and others just don't?

473
00:19:04,620 --> 00:19:07,890
Why people rave about one
business and ignore another?

474
00:19:07,890 --> 00:19:09,660
Well, "Purple Cow" believes

475
00:19:09,660 --> 00:19:11,970
that the key is being remarkable.

476
00:19:11,970 --> 00:19:15,330
Every marketer is traditionally
aware of the five Ps,

477
00:19:15,330 --> 00:19:19,800
product, positioning, pricing,
publicity, and promotion.

478
00:19:19,800 --> 00:19:24,300
However, this book introduces
a sixth P, the purple cow.

479
00:19:24,300 --> 00:19:27,060
I know this might sound a bit
strange, but stick with me.

480
00:19:27,060 --> 00:19:29,220
Imagine you are driving
along a country road

481
00:19:29,220 --> 00:19:31,560
and you see a brown cow grazing.

482
00:19:31,560 --> 00:19:34,590
It's so common that you hardly notice it,

483
00:19:34,590 --> 00:19:38,220
much like the barrage of everyday
marketing and advertising.

484
00:19:38,220 --> 00:19:41,790
Now, imagine instead seeing a purple cow,

485
00:19:41,790 --> 00:19:43,530
you'd stop the car, you'd get out,

486
00:19:43,530 --> 00:19:45,060
you'd take a selfie with it.

487
00:19:45,060 --> 00:19:48,720
It's noteworthy and you
can't help but talk about it.

488
00:19:48,720 --> 00:19:51,600
Imagine if your business
was like that purple cow,

489
00:19:51,600 --> 00:19:53,820
compelling people to talk about it.

490
00:19:53,820 --> 00:19:57,240
So think about what makes
your business unique,

491
00:19:57,240 --> 00:20:00,060
what do you do better than anyone else?

492
00:20:00,060 --> 00:20:03,300
What unique value do you
offer to your customers?

493
00:20:03,300 --> 00:20:05,880
Lots of businesses are
using TikTok and YouTube

494
00:20:05,880 --> 00:20:08,640
to stand out, especially restaurants,

495
00:20:08,640 --> 00:20:10,380
who are coming up with unique dishes

496
00:20:10,380 --> 00:20:14,070
that they're using as purple
cows to draw in customers.

497
00:20:14,070 --> 00:20:16,710
If you want to dive more
into creating videos,

498
00:20:16,710 --> 00:20:20,280
then "YouTube Secrets," which
is down here just like that,

499
00:20:20,280 --> 00:20:24,120
gives you a really good insight
into making viral content.

500
00:20:24,120 --> 00:20:26,610
Step two, gather real world data.

501
00:20:26,610 --> 00:20:29,700
If you want any hope marketing
your product or service,

502
00:20:29,700 --> 00:20:32,250
then you need to know what
people think about it.

503
00:20:32,250 --> 00:20:34,800
However, this is where most
people make the mistake

504
00:20:34,800 --> 00:20:37,740
of asking the people closest
to them for their thoughts.

505
00:20:37,740 --> 00:20:40,770
This results in them just
giving you blind encouragement

506
00:20:40,770 --> 00:20:43,020
and generic support, which might be good

507
00:20:43,020 --> 00:20:44,490
for boosting your ego,

508
00:20:44,490 --> 00:20:46,417
but it won't help you market your product.

509
00:20:46,417 --> 00:20:49,770
"The Mom Test" offers a
solution to this problem.

510
00:20:49,770 --> 00:20:51,577
It says that instead of saying,

511
00:20:51,577 --> 00:20:54,330
"Here's my business, what do you think?"

512
00:20:54,330 --> 00:20:56,490
You should instead ask about their life

513
00:20:56,490 --> 00:20:58,470
in the context of your business.

514
00:20:58,470 --> 00:20:59,910
I know this sounds confusing,

515
00:20:59,910 --> 00:21:02,010
but let me give you an example.

516
00:21:02,010 --> 00:21:04,380
Say you are starting an
online course business

517
00:21:04,380 --> 00:21:06,600
that teaches people how to play the piano

518
00:21:06,600 --> 00:21:08,640
from the comfort of their own home.

519
00:21:08,640 --> 00:21:10,470
Instead of asking your friends and family

520
00:21:10,470 --> 00:21:13,080
if they liked the idea, talk about them,

521
00:21:13,080 --> 00:21:14,370
if they play the piano,

522
00:21:14,370 --> 00:21:17,460
you could ask about the
initial challenges they faced,

523
00:21:17,460 --> 00:21:19,440
the solutions they seeked out,

524
00:21:19,440 --> 00:21:22,620
and any frustrations they had
with the solutions they found.

525
00:21:22,620 --> 00:21:24,090
If they don't play the piano,

526
00:21:24,090 --> 00:21:26,280
you could slightly tweak the questions.

527
00:21:26,280 --> 00:21:28,110
This is an extremely smart way

528
00:21:28,110 --> 00:21:30,390
to get useful data on your business

529
00:21:30,390 --> 00:21:34,080
as it's almost impossible
for anyone, even your mum,

530
00:21:34,080 --> 00:21:36,270
to give you blind support
and encouragement.

531
00:21:36,270 --> 00:21:40,950
You can use this information
to help identify "Blue Oceans,"

532
00:21:40,950 --> 00:21:44,100
which are areas of a market
with low competition,

533
00:21:44,100 --> 00:21:45,930
but very high demand.

534
00:21:45,930 --> 00:21:49,200
Step three, establish your brand message.

535
00:21:49,200 --> 00:21:50,820
Despite having a USP

536
00:21:50,820 --> 00:21:53,880
and necessary data, many
new entrepreneurs struggle

537
00:21:53,880 --> 00:21:56,460
to capture the attention
of potential customers.

538
00:21:56,460 --> 00:21:58,950
People don't like feeling sold to

539
00:21:58,950 --> 00:22:01,140
and because of this,
it's hard to get someone

540
00:22:01,140 --> 00:22:03,420
to listen long enough to actually get them

541
00:22:03,420 --> 00:22:04,897
to want to buy from you.

542
00:22:04,897 --> 00:22:08,160
"Building A Story Brand"
says the solution is used

543
00:22:08,160 --> 00:22:11,070
in a specific story
structure in your marketing

544
00:22:11,070 --> 00:22:15,090
that cuts through the noise
and holds people's attention.

545
00:22:15,090 --> 00:22:17,400
You first need to create a character.

546
00:22:17,400 --> 00:22:19,530
This character isn't your business,

547
00:22:19,530 --> 00:22:21,600
it's your target customer.

548
00:22:21,600 --> 00:22:23,640
This is because everyone sees themselves

549
00:22:23,640 --> 00:22:25,950
as the main character in their story.

550
00:22:25,950 --> 00:22:28,890
You need to make it very clear
what this character wants.

551
00:22:28,890 --> 00:22:32,070
At this stage, it's best to
stick to the universal desires,

552
00:22:32,070 --> 00:22:34,320
like, building wealth and status,

553
00:22:34,320 --> 00:22:37,500
higher quality relationships
or increased health.

554
00:22:37,500 --> 00:22:40,890
Next, your character should
face a specific problem related

555
00:22:40,890 --> 00:22:43,530
to your product that
they want to overcome.

556
00:22:43,530 --> 00:22:44,490
For instance,

557
00:22:44,490 --> 00:22:46,800
if you are running a
piano teaching business,

558
00:22:46,800 --> 00:22:49,677
the external problem
they'd want to overcome is,

559
00:22:49,677 --> 00:22:51,780
not being good enough
at playing the piano.

560
00:22:51,780 --> 00:22:53,910
Their internal struggle
might be questioning

561
00:22:53,910 --> 00:22:56,160
their own abilities and
if they're good enough,

562
00:22:56,160 --> 00:22:58,710
here, you can introduce
your business as their guide

563
00:22:58,710 --> 00:23:00,390
to overcoming this problem

564
00:23:00,390 --> 00:23:04,080
and share past success stories
to establish your authority.

565
00:23:04,080 --> 00:23:07,350
Both these elements build
trust in you and your business.

566
00:23:07,350 --> 00:23:09,390
You need to be able to
get this message across

567
00:23:09,390 --> 00:23:10,830
in multiple formats,

568
00:23:10,830 --> 00:23:13,200
but one of the most
crucial is with writing.

569
00:23:13,200 --> 00:23:16,770
That's why it's worth giving
"Copywriting Secrets" a read.

570
00:23:16,770 --> 00:23:17,940
The main takeaway here is

571
00:23:17,940 --> 00:23:19,950
to portray your potential customers

572
00:23:19,950 --> 00:23:21,990
as heroes in your marketing.

573
00:23:21,990 --> 00:23:23,310
This narrative structure,

574
00:23:23,310 --> 00:23:25,620
commonly known as "The Hero's Journey,"

575
00:23:25,620 --> 00:23:28,170
is frequently used in TV shows and films.

576
00:23:28,170 --> 00:23:31,170
If you make people into
the hero of your story,

577
00:23:31,170 --> 00:23:32,550
they'll sit up and listen.

578
00:23:32,550 --> 00:23:35,130
Once you've sold to someone
once, it's so much easier

579
00:23:35,130 --> 00:23:37,260
to sell to them again
with the right strategy.

580
00:23:37,260 --> 00:23:39,960
That's why step four is create upsells.

581
00:23:39,960 --> 00:23:43,020
It's actually shocking how
many businesses are leaving

582
00:23:43,020 --> 00:23:46,537
so much money on the table
by not using this technique.

583
00:23:46,537 --> 00:23:48,750
"Dotcom Secrets" teaches you exactly

584
00:23:48,750 --> 00:23:52,170
how to build a value ladder
and sell higher price products

585
00:23:52,170 --> 00:23:54,870
and services to your existing customers.

586
00:23:54,870 --> 00:23:56,610
You've probably already
seen this in action

587
00:23:56,610 --> 00:23:59,640
at your local dentist and
not even thought about it.

588
00:23:59,640 --> 00:24:01,740
Normally, a dental practice starts off

589
00:24:01,740 --> 00:24:03,900
by selling you a simple checkup.

590
00:24:03,900 --> 00:24:06,300
Next, they might offer you teeth cleaning,

591
00:24:06,300 --> 00:24:07,740
then teeth whitening.

592
00:24:07,740 --> 00:24:10,470
After that, a retainer
and before you know it,

593
00:24:10,470 --> 00:24:12,660
they've pushed you all
the way up the ladder

594
00:24:12,660 --> 00:24:15,990
to their most expensive
product, cosmetic surgery.

595
00:24:15,990 --> 00:24:17,100
This approach can be applied

596
00:24:17,100 --> 00:24:19,080
to any business you are starting.

597
00:24:19,080 --> 00:24:20,880
If customers have a great experience

598
00:24:20,880 --> 00:24:22,800
with your lower priced products,

599
00:24:22,800 --> 00:24:24,900
they're likely to continue
climbing the ladder.

600
00:24:24,900 --> 00:24:26,910
It's also important to remember

601
00:24:26,910 --> 00:24:28,620
if you don't provide options for them

602
00:24:28,620 --> 00:24:30,360
to spend more money with you,

603
00:24:30,360 --> 00:24:32,640
they may end up going to
one of your competitors.

604
00:24:32,640 --> 00:24:36,007
Ideally, you shouldn't have
to upsell people face to face.

605
00:24:36,007 --> 00:24:38,700
"Expert Secrets" outlines
a way you can use

606
00:24:38,700 --> 00:24:42,330
the perfect webinar model to
upsell many people at once,

607
00:24:42,330 --> 00:24:44,190
whilst keeping that personal feel,

608
00:24:44,190 --> 00:24:47,040
but how do you make sure you
never run out of customers

609
00:24:47,040 --> 00:24:48,660
to climb your value ladder?

610
00:24:48,660 --> 00:24:51,360
That's where step five
comes in, driving up demand.

611
00:24:51,360 --> 00:24:53,370
If you followed all of the steps so far,

612
00:24:53,370 --> 00:24:55,290
you should have plenty of demand,

613
00:24:55,290 --> 00:24:57,300
but instead of trying to sell to everyone,

614
00:24:57,300 --> 00:24:59,820
you could try and limit
your product or service

615
00:24:59,820 --> 00:25:01,087
and increase the price.

616
00:25:01,087 --> 00:25:03,303
"Oversubscribed" states that every product

617
00:25:03,303 --> 00:25:07,170
that is oversubscribed has
people that didn't get it,

618
00:25:07,170 --> 00:25:09,240
even though they were willing to buy it.

619
00:25:09,240 --> 00:25:11,850
Rolex has mastered this
strategy better than most.

620
00:25:11,850 --> 00:25:13,650
If you wanna purchase a new Rolex,

621
00:25:13,650 --> 00:25:15,600
you have to visit an authorized store,

622
00:25:15,600 --> 00:25:18,900
join a long waiting
list and patiently wait.

623
00:25:18,900 --> 00:25:20,790
This process can take up to four years

624
00:25:20,790 --> 00:25:23,100
before you're offered the
chance to buy a watch.

625
00:25:23,100 --> 00:25:25,530
Some people never receive the call

626
00:25:25,530 --> 00:25:27,690
as Rolex doesn't deem
them the right customer

627
00:25:27,690 --> 00:25:28,650
for their brand.

628
00:25:28,650 --> 00:25:31,110
Does this sound a bit snobby? Possibly.

629
00:25:31,110 --> 00:25:33,450
But does it work? Absolutely.

630
00:25:33,450 --> 00:25:36,090
If your product is seen as oversubscribed,

631
00:25:36,090 --> 00:25:38,520
competition becomes less of a concern

632
00:25:38,520 --> 00:25:40,260
and you have the flexibility

633
00:25:40,260 --> 00:25:42,540
to set your prices as you see fit.

634
00:25:42,540 --> 00:25:43,500
It's all about following

635
00:25:43,500 --> 00:25:45,810
the "Don't Make Me Think" principle.

636
00:25:45,810 --> 00:25:48,270
You've got to make it very
easy for your customers

637
00:25:48,270 --> 00:25:50,960
to understand your website and messaging.

638
00:25:50,960 --> 00:25:53,598
(energetic upbeat music)

639
00:25:53,598 --> 00:25:56,010
(paper rustling)

640
00:25:56,010 --> 00:25:58,710
So, how to manage your money like the 1%.

641
00:25:58,710 --> 00:26:01,530
This section is absolutely crucial.

642
00:26:01,530 --> 00:26:03,930
You won't believe how
many people are amazing

643
00:26:03,930 --> 00:26:05,700
at almost everything else

644
00:26:05,700 --> 00:26:08,370
but struggle when it comes
to handling their cash.

645
00:26:08,370 --> 00:26:10,020
This is a big reason why one out

646
00:26:10,020 --> 00:26:13,200
of every three people
earning over 100 grand a year

647
00:26:13,200 --> 00:26:15,390
are still living paycheck to paycheck.

648
00:26:15,390 --> 00:26:17,587
Step one, monitor your finances.

649
00:26:17,587 --> 00:26:19,110
"The Total Money Makeover,"

650
00:26:19,110 --> 00:26:22,320
while not specifically
focused on business finances,

651
00:26:22,320 --> 00:26:24,210
it does offer some valuable principles

652
00:26:24,210 --> 00:26:26,070
for keeping your money under control,

653
00:26:26,070 --> 00:26:28,950
which can be applied to
business finances as well.

654
00:26:28,950 --> 00:26:31,770
Here's the major takeaway
for all you entrepreneurs,

655
00:26:31,770 --> 00:26:34,680
keep a sharp eye on your finances.

656
00:26:34,680 --> 00:26:37,740
It's so easy to get caught up
in the daily hustle and bustle

657
00:26:37,740 --> 00:26:39,030
of running your business,

658
00:26:39,030 --> 00:26:41,220
that you lose sight of your numbers

659
00:26:41,220 --> 00:26:43,860
and before you know it,
you're in a financial pickle

660
00:26:43,860 --> 00:26:45,660
without even realizing it.

661
00:26:45,660 --> 00:26:46,493
Think about it.

662
00:26:46,493 --> 00:26:48,780
Financial laziness is a lot sneakier

663
00:26:48,780 --> 00:26:50,430
than physical laziness.

664
00:26:50,430 --> 00:26:52,200
It's not like you are
forced to confront it

665
00:26:52,200 --> 00:26:53,790
every time you look in the mirror,

666
00:26:53,790 --> 00:26:55,740
you can just brush it under the rug

667
00:26:55,740 --> 00:26:58,890
and only start panicking
when it's too late.

668
00:26:58,890 --> 00:27:00,600
So if you feel like you've lost touch

669
00:27:00,600 --> 00:27:02,370
with your financial situation,

670
00:27:02,370 --> 00:27:04,410
here's a little reality check for you.

671
00:27:04,410 --> 00:27:05,820
Ask yourself this,

672
00:27:05,820 --> 00:27:08,640
if all your revenue
stopped coming in tomorrow,

673
00:27:08,640 --> 00:27:10,110
could you keep your business afloat

674
00:27:10,110 --> 00:27:11,550
for at least three months?

675
00:27:11,550 --> 00:27:14,190
If the answer's no, then
sorry to break it to you,

676
00:27:14,190 --> 00:27:16,140
but you're financially outta shape.

677
00:27:16,140 --> 00:27:18,210
It's time to hit the financial gym.

678
00:27:18,210 --> 00:27:21,240
That brings us onto step
two, remain profitable.

679
00:27:21,240 --> 00:27:22,590
You might think being profitable,

680
00:27:22,590 --> 00:27:24,810
it's the same as being financially stable,

681
00:27:24,810 --> 00:27:26,610
but they're actually pretty different.

682
00:27:26,610 --> 00:27:29,910
Most businesses morph
into cash hungry beasts.

683
00:27:29,910 --> 00:27:32,160
This is because when most
ambitious entrepreneurs

684
00:27:32,160 --> 00:27:34,770
make sales, they pump
most of that sales revenue

685
00:27:34,770 --> 00:27:38,040
back into growing their
business and guess what happens?

686
00:27:38,040 --> 00:27:39,630
Their expenses shoot up,

687
00:27:39,630 --> 00:27:40,980
but they think it's fine

688
00:27:40,980 --> 00:27:43,590
as they make their profits
once their business is bigger.

689
00:27:43,590 --> 00:27:45,420
However, the profits never come

690
00:27:45,420 --> 00:27:48,360
because when sales drop,
expenses stay high,

691
00:27:48,360 --> 00:27:50,640
which causes the business to bleed money

692
00:27:50,640 --> 00:27:52,117
and eventually collapse.

693
00:27:52,117 --> 00:27:54,420
"Profit First" urges entrepreneurs

694
00:27:54,420 --> 00:27:57,330
to think about profit in a different way.

695
00:27:57,330 --> 00:28:01,920
The traditional way is sales
minus expenses equals profit,

696
00:28:01,920 --> 00:28:03,307
but "Profit First" says,

697
00:28:03,307 --> 00:28:05,730
"You should instead
flip the formula around

698
00:28:05,730 --> 00:28:09,150
to sales minus profit equals expenses."

699
00:28:09,150 --> 00:28:11,070
By taking a portion of each sale

700
00:28:11,070 --> 00:28:13,920
and allocating it to profit,
you force your business

701
00:28:13,920 --> 00:28:15,240
to become more efficient.

702
00:28:15,240 --> 00:28:17,970
That's the funny thing about
having less money to spend.

703
00:28:17,970 --> 00:28:20,760
You actually start to
discover you can run things

704
00:28:20,760 --> 00:28:22,980
for far less than you initially thought.

705
00:28:22,980 --> 00:28:25,500
Step three, plan for taxes.

706
00:28:25,500 --> 00:28:27,870
Did you know the average
taxpayer in the US

707
00:28:27,870 --> 00:28:32,347
will spend an estimated $524,625,

708
00:28:34,290 --> 00:28:36,900
around a third of their lifetime earnings

709
00:28:36,900 --> 00:28:39,720
on various state and federal taxes,

710
00:28:39,720 --> 00:28:41,400
and that's the average person.

711
00:28:41,400 --> 00:28:44,190
As an entrepreneur, you're
gonna be paying a lot more.

712
00:28:44,190 --> 00:28:46,410
Many people think the tax system is evil

713
00:28:46,410 --> 00:28:48,240
and just there to get your money.

714
00:28:48,240 --> 00:28:50,430
However, "Tax-Free Wealth" states

715
00:28:50,430 --> 00:28:53,340
that the IRS has written
a tax code in a way

716
00:28:53,340 --> 00:28:55,710
to save us money, that's right.

717
00:28:55,710 --> 00:28:58,260
The book states that the
current tax code contains

718
00:28:58,260 --> 00:29:03,180
over 5,800 pages and
only 30 of those address

719
00:29:03,180 --> 00:29:04,830
how to pay taxes.

720
00:29:04,830 --> 00:29:09,390
This means that the IRS
dedicated 5,770 pages

721
00:29:09,390 --> 00:29:14,280
or 99.5% of the code
to help us avoid taxes

722
00:29:14,280 --> 00:29:16,140
and therefore increase our wealth.

723
00:29:16,140 --> 00:29:17,670
It's very similar in the UK

724
00:29:17,670 --> 00:29:19,080
and other Western countries,

725
00:29:19,080 --> 00:29:21,420
as they want to help stimulate the economy

726
00:29:21,420 --> 00:29:23,070
above taking your money.

727
00:29:23,070 --> 00:29:25,680
That's why it's really worth
getting a great accountant

728
00:29:25,680 --> 00:29:27,000
who can take advantage

729
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:29,430
of all the tax breaks you are entitled to.

730
00:29:29,430 --> 00:29:31,860
Step four is playing your own game.

731
00:29:31,860 --> 00:29:33,660
To be a successful entrepreneur,

732
00:29:33,660 --> 00:29:35,880
you need to base your decisions on data

733
00:29:35,880 --> 00:29:37,627
and not be easily led by others.

734
00:29:37,627 --> 00:29:39,120
"The Intelligent Investor"

735
00:29:39,120 --> 00:29:42,150
is one of my all-time
favorite investing books.

736
00:29:42,150 --> 00:29:45,000
It discusses a scenario
that perfectly applies

737
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:47,430
to both running a business
and investing in one.

738
00:29:47,430 --> 00:29:51,120
Imagine owning a small
business that costs you $1,000.

739
00:29:51,120 --> 00:29:54,870
and you have a business
partner called Mr. Market.

740
00:29:54,870 --> 00:29:56,460
Every single day he pops in

741
00:29:56,460 --> 00:29:58,650
and tells you how much
he thinks your piece

742
00:29:58,650 --> 00:30:00,060
of the business is worth.

743
00:30:00,060 --> 00:30:03,360
Not only that, but he's
always ready to buy your share

744
00:30:03,360 --> 00:30:05,610
or sell you more at that price.

745
00:30:05,610 --> 00:30:09,030
Sometimes Mr. Market seems
to hit the nail on the head.

746
00:30:09,030 --> 00:30:10,680
His valuation makes sense

747
00:30:10,680 --> 00:30:12,690
based on what's happening in the business

748
00:30:12,690 --> 00:30:14,520
and what the future looks like,

749
00:30:14,520 --> 00:30:17,820
but at other times, Mr.
Market gets a bit carried away

750
00:30:17,820 --> 00:30:20,130
with his emotions and the price he offers

751
00:30:20,130 --> 00:30:22,770
can seem, well, a little bit crazy.

752
00:30:22,770 --> 00:30:26,430
Now, if you are a savvy investor
or a smart business person,

753
00:30:26,430 --> 00:30:28,590
are you gonna let Mr. Market's daily chat

754
00:30:28,590 --> 00:30:32,070
sway your own opinion of your
$1,000 stake in the business?

755
00:30:32,070 --> 00:30:33,660
Well, you shouldn't.

756
00:30:33,660 --> 00:30:36,780
Most of the time you'd be
smarter to make up your own mind

757
00:30:36,780 --> 00:30:38,610
about what your investment is worth.

758
00:30:38,610 --> 00:30:41,490
Remember, most people are
driven by their emotions.

759
00:30:41,490 --> 00:30:43,410
If you wanna see long-term success,

760
00:30:43,410 --> 00:30:44,520
you've gotta think rationally

761
00:30:44,520 --> 00:30:46,200
with your business and investment.

762
00:30:46,200 --> 00:30:48,870
Step five is mitigating risks.

763
00:30:48,870 --> 00:30:50,970
When you're in the early
stages of business,

764
00:30:50,970 --> 00:30:53,880
you have to take big
risks and think quickly,

765
00:30:53,880 --> 00:30:57,300
but as your business grows,
it makes sense to slow down

766
00:30:57,300 --> 00:30:58,860
and think about mitigating

767
00:30:58,860 --> 00:31:01,410
as many unnecessary risks as possible.

768
00:31:01,410 --> 00:31:04,830
I've had many multimillionaire
friends that didn't do this

769
00:31:04,830 --> 00:31:06,810
and ended up losing everything.

770
00:31:06,810 --> 00:31:09,180
Thinking fast and slow outlines

771
00:31:09,180 --> 00:31:12,360
that your brain actually
has two ways of thinking.

772
00:31:12,360 --> 00:31:14,940
System one is fast and intuitive,

773
00:31:14,940 --> 00:31:17,580
and system two is slow and analytical.

774
00:31:17,580 --> 00:31:18,870
Listen to this question

775
00:31:18,870 --> 00:31:22,050
and answer it in your
head as fast as you can.

776
00:31:22,050 --> 00:31:25,560
A bat and ball cost $1
and 10 cents in total.

777
00:31:25,560 --> 00:31:28,320
The bat costs $1 more than the ball.

778
00:31:28,320 --> 00:31:30,060
How much does the ball cost?

779
00:31:30,060 --> 00:31:32,220
If you're like most people,
you'll have answered

780
00:31:32,220 --> 00:31:35,550
